# Cubit and State — Project Patterns

> For general architecture rules (layers, dependencies, naming), see `.cursorrules`.

---

## Async flows in State — use sealed classes

When a State manages async operations (load, submit), model each flow as a sealed class instead of `bool loading + bool failure`.

**Why:** sealed classes remove invalid boolean combinations and force exhaustive handling in the widget via pattern matching.

```dart
// ✅ BOM
sealed class AddressesFlow extends Equatable { const AddressesFlow(); }
final class AddressesFlowLoading extends AddressesFlow {
  @override List<Object?> get props => [];
}
final class AddressesFlowLoaded extends AddressesFlow {
  final List<AddressEntity> addresses;
  const AddressesFlowLoaded(this.addresses);
  @override List<Object?> get props => [addresses];
}
final class AddressesFlowError extends AddressesFlow {
  final String message;
  const AddressesFlowError(this.message);
  @override List<Object?> get props => [message];
}

// ❌ BAD — allows loading: true and failure: true at the same time
bool loadingAddresses;
bool failureAddresses;
String? errorMessage;
```

### Sealed class rules

- The sealed base extends `Equatable`
- Each subclass implements `props` with its own data
- Subclasses with no data: `props => []`
- Default prefix: `<FlowName>Loading`, `<FlowName>Loaded`, `<FlowName>Error`
- Add `<FlowName>Initial` or `<FlowName>Idle` when the flow has a neutral initial state

### In the widget, use exhaustive pattern matching

```dart
switch (state.addressesFlow) {
  AddressesFlowLoading()              => CircularProgressIndicator(),
  AddressesFlowError(:final message)  => _RetryView(message),
  AddressesFlowLoaded(:final addresses) => _AddressDropdown(addresses),
  AddressesFlowInitial()              => SizedBox.shrink(),
}
```

